# Storage Technology – Cornell Notes

| Cues / Keywords | Notes (Detailed Explanation) |
|----------------|-----------------------------|
| Storage basics | Storage technology is the foundation of any computing system, because it is responsible for holding all types of digital data such as operating system files, applications, documents, and multimedia. In simple words, storage allows a system to remember information even after the power is switched off. |
| Primary vs Secondary | Storage is broadly divided into primary and secondary types. Primary storage is directly connected to the CPU and is used for temporary data processing, whereas secondary storage is used for long-term data storage. Primary storage is faster but smaller in size, while secondary storage is slower but provides large capacity at a lower cost. |
| RAM concept | RAM is the most important primary storage component, which temporarily stores data that is actively used by programs. It is volatile, meaning data is lost when power is removed. RAM enables fast execution because CPU can directly access it without delay. |
| ROM concept | ROM is non-volatile memory that permanently stores basic instructions required for system startup. It contains firmware that helps in booting the device, ensuring the system can load the operating system correctly. |
| Need for secondary storage | Since RAM cannot store data permanently, secondary storage becomes essential. It is designed to hold data for long periods, ensuring files remain intact even when the system is powered off. |
| HDD working | Hard Disk Drive is a traditional storage device that uses magnetic disks rotating at high speeds. Data is written and read using a mechanical arm. Because of moving parts, it is slower and more susceptible to physical wear and tear, but it remains cost-effective for large data storage. |
| SSD working | Solid State Drive is an advanced storage technology that uses flash memory instead of mechanical parts. Because it has no moving components, it is much faster, reliable, energy-efficient, and silent. SSDs significantly improve system performance, especially for booting and application loading. |
| Flash storage | Flash-based storage devices such as pen drives and memory cards are portable and commonly used for file transfer. They are widely used in mobiles, cameras, and embedded systems due to compact size and ease of use. |
| Optical storage | Optical storage like CDs and DVDs uses laser technology to read and write data. Although it was popular earlier, it is now mostly replaced by faster and more convenient storage options like SSDs and cloud storage. |
| Capacity & units | Storage capacity refers to how much data a device can hold. It is measured in units like kilobytes, megabytes, gigabytes, terabytes, and even petabytes in large-scale systems. As technology advances, the capacity continues to increase while cost decreases. |
| Performance factors | The performance of storage depends on multiple factors including read speed, write speed, latency, and throughput. Faster storage results in quicker data access and improved system responsiveness, which is especially important for applications like databases and gaming. |
| File system idea | A file system defines how data is organised and stored on a storage device. It ensures files are properly managed and accessible. Different operating systems use different file systems such as NTFS in Windows and ext4 in Linux. |
| Interfaces (SATA, NVMe) | Storage devices connect to the system through interfaces. SATA is a widely used standard but offers limited speed. NVMe is a modern high-speed interface that uses PCIe lanes and provides significantly higher performance, making it ideal for SSDs. |
| Mobile storage (UFS) | In mobile devices, UFS (Universal Flash Storage) is widely used because it provides high speed and supports advanced features like command queuing and full-duplex communication. It is much faster and efficient compared to older eMMC storage. |
| RAID concept | RAID is a technique used to combine multiple storage devices into a single logical unit. It improves performance, reliability, or both. Some configurations focus on speed, while others ensure data redundancy in case of disk failure. |
| Cloud storage | Cloud storage is a modern approach where data is stored on remote servers and accessed through the internet. It provides flexibility, scalability, and easy backup. However, it depends on internet connectivity and requires proper security measures. |
| Storage hierarchy | Storage in a system is organised in a hierarchy based on speed, cost, and capacity. Faster storage like registers and cache is expensive and small, while slower storage like HDDs is cheaper and larger. This hierarchy helps in optimising system performance. |
| Backup importance | Data backup is a critical aspect of storage systems. It ensures that data can be recovered in case of hardware failure, system crash, or accidental deletion. Different methods like full, incremental, and differential backups are used depending on requirements. |
| Future trends | Storage technology is continuously evolving. Advanced concepts like 3D NAND are increasing storage density in SSDs, and emerging ideas like AI-driven storage management and DNA storage are being explored for future applications. |
